Autofill Algorithm Overview
CrossFire uses a depth-first search with backtracking, combined with heuristic word selection and scoring, to fill the crossword grid.

1. Search Engine
The core is a DFS (Depth-First Search) with two implementations:
* DepthFirstSearch — basic DFS with backtracking
* DepthPlusSearch — enhanced version that generates and evaluates multiple successors per node
Each state in the search is a GridSearchNode representing the current partially-filled grid. When the algorithm hits a dead end (no valid candidates for a slot), it backtracks to try a different word at the previous slot. Search depth is bounded by a maxDepth parameter.

2. Choosing Which Slot to Fill Next (Fill Order)
The algorithm picks the next empty word slot using one of four strategies, controlled by a FillOrder enum:
Strategy	Method	Behavior
Standard	chooseWordToFillStd	Traditional ordering
Greedy	chooseWordToFillGreedy	Picks the slot with the fewest/easiest candidates (most constrained first — classic CSP heuristic)
Quality	chooseWordToFillQuality	Picks based on a quality scoring function
Frontier	chooseWordToFillFrontier	Fills from the edges inward, using findIsland() and findIslandNeighbors() to detect boundaries
The user can select which strategy to use in the Fill Settings dialog.

3. Candidate Word Generation
For the chosen slot, the CandidateGenerator (running on a separate CandidateThread for parallelism):
1. Pattern-matches against the dictionary — the slot has a length and some letters already fixed by crossing words, so it filters default.dict to words matching that pattern
2. Filters by minimum score — any word below minCandidateScore (configurable via minAutoFillScore) is discarded
3. Returns a ranked list of candidate words

4. Scoring System
Words and grid states are scored using multiple components:
* Word Score — from the .dict file (the ;75 values), representing word quality/commonness
* Cross Score — how well a word plays with its crossing words
* Grid Score — overall solution quality
* Final/Complete Score — combined metric
The scoring backend (ScoreDatabase) supports multiple sources:
* Score from the .dict file itself
* A separate CrossFire score database
* Fixed constant scores
* "Highest score" mode (takes the best from multiple dictionaries)
Two weighting factors let users tune the balance:
* depthFirstFactor — how much to favor deeper exploration
* qualityFactor — how much to favor word quality

5. Successor Expansion
For each candidate word in the chosen slot:
1. Place the word in the grid → creates a new GridSearchNode
2. Check if all crossing slots still have valid candidates (implicit constraint checking)
3. If a crossing slot has zero valid candidates, this branch is pruned
4. Otherwise, add it as a successor and recurse
This is constraint enforcement through candidate filtering — not full arc consistency (AC-3), but effective pruning nonetheless.

6. Backtracking & Termination
* If no candidates work for a slot → backtrack (log: "selection dead-end node: depth = X")
* If the grid is completely filled → solution found, scored and presented
* If all branches exhausted → "*** Unfillable Grid ***"
* User can stop the search at any time; the best partial fill found so far can be inspected via "Show sample fill"

7. User-Facing Controls
Control	Effect
Min Autofill Score	Threshold — higher = only common words, lower = obscure words allowed
Fill Order	Strategy selection (standard/greedy/quality/frontier)
Auto-enter complete	Automatically fills cells that have only one possible letter
Insert complete fill	Applies the found solution to the grid
Show sample fill	Preview current best attempt
Best location	Highlights the optimal next word to manually fill
In Summary
The algorithm is essentially: pick the most constrained empty slot → generate candidate words from the dictionary above a score threshold → try each one via DFS → prune branches where crossings become impossible → backtrack on dead ends → return the highest-scoring complete fill found. The frontier/greedy/quality heuristics and parallel candidate generation make it efficient enough to fill typical crossword grids.
